CSS Selectors and its types with example

ChatGPT
CSS selectors are patterns used to select and style HTML elements in a document. They define the criteria for selecting specific elements, and CSS rules are applied to those elements. Here are some common CSS selectors and their types:

1. Universal Selector *:
Selects all elements on the page.
Example: * { margin: 0; padding: 0; }
2. Type Selector:
Selects all elements of a specified type.
Example: p { color: blue; }
3. Class Selector .classname:
Selects all elements with a specified class attribute.
Example: .highlight { background-color: yellow; }
4. ID Selector #id:
Selects a single element with a specified id attribute.
Example: #header { font-size: 20px; }
5. Attribute Selector [attribute=value]:
Selects elements with a specific attribute and value.
Example: [type="text"] { border: 1px solid #ccc; }
6. Descendant Selector ancestor descendant:
Selects all descendants of a specified ancestor.
Example: article p { font-style: italic; }
7. Child Selector parent > child:
Selects all direct children of a specified parent.
Example: ul > li { list-style-type: square; }
8. Adjacent Sibling Selector element + element:
Selects an element that is immediately preceded by a specified element.
Example: h2 + p { font-weight: bold; }
9. General Sibling Selector element ~ element:
Selects all siblings that follow a specified element.
Example: h2 ~ p { color: red; }
10. Pseudo-classes :pseudo-class:
Selects elements based on their state or position.
Example: a:hover { text-decoration: underline; }
11. Pseudo-elements ::pseudo-element:
Selects parts of an element or generates content.
Example: p::first-line { font-weight: bold; }
12. Grouping Selector:
Groups multiple selectors together to apply the same style.
Example: h1, h2, h3 { color: green; }
